[Transmissible gastroenteritis (TGE) is an enteric disease of pigs caused by TGE virus (TGEV), a member of the Coronaviridae. Since 1984, a distinct respiratory variant (porcine respiratory coronavirus or PRCV) has spread throughout many parts of the world and is now found in most countries where surveys for it have been conducted, one exception being Oceania. Occurrences of TGE have become more sporadic. The disease is still reported on an occasional basis from parts of Europe, North America and Asia. TGEV multiplies in and damages the enterocytes lining the small intestine, producing villous atrophy and enteritis. Diarrhoea and vomiting occur in pigs of all ages; mortality is highest in neonates. Extra-intestinal sites of virus multiplication include the respiratory tract and mammary tissues, but the virus is most readily isolated from the intestinal tract and from faeces.

For the above and additional background information, including diagnostic methods and references, please refer to the OIE Terrestrial Manual 2014, Chapter 2.8.11, Transmissible Gastroenteritis, at http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/tahm/2.08.11_TRANSMISSIBLE_GASTRO.pdf.

TGE has no public health implications (http://www.animalhealthaustralia.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2011/04/TGE3.1-09FINAL20Sep12.pdf).

A map of the Argentina's administrative divisions can be seen at http://www.ephotopix.com/image/south_america/argentina_political_map.gif. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2998238,42888.]
